05725nam a22009495i 9780520922327DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20201999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209223277 a10.1525/97805209223272doi  a(DE-B1597)570101  a(OCoLC)1202625367  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPA6554.P5bZ89 1999eb 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a871/.12211 aTrout, Dennis E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPaulinus of Nola :bLife, Letters, and Poems /cDennis E. Trout.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (348 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransformation of the Classical Heritage ;v2700tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tPREFACE -- tTHE NATALICIA: CHRONOLOGY AND CONCORDANCE -- tCHAPTER 1. Claiming Paulinus -- tCHAPTER 2. The Early Years -- tCHAPTER 3. From Otium Ruris to Contemptus Mundi -- tCHAPTER 4. Renunciation and Ordination -- tCHAPTER 5. Paulinus at Nola 395-431 -- tCHAPTER 6. Salvation Economics -- tCHAPTER 7. The Cult of Saint Felix -- tCHAPTER 8. Paulinus and Latin Christian Culture -- tCHAPTER 9. The Final Years -- tCHAPTER 10. Epilogue -- tAPPENDIX A: THE CORPUS -- tAPPENDIX B: EARLY CHRONOLOGY AND CURSUS HONORUM -- tAPPENDIX C: SELECT CHRONOLOGY -- tAPPENDIX D: URANIUS'S DE OBITU SAJVCTIPAULINI -- tSELECT BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tGENERAL INDEX -- tINDEX LOCORUM0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis study offers a comprehensive reconsideration of the life and literary works of Paulinus of Nola (ca. 352-431), a Roman senator who renounced his political career and secular lifestyle to become a monk, bishop, impresario of a saint's cult, and prominent Christian poet. Dennis Trout considers all the ancient materials and modern commentary on Paulinus, and also delves into archaeological and historical sources to illuminate the various settings in which we see this late ancient man at work. This vivid historical biography traces Paulinus's intellectual and spiritual journey and at the same time explores many facets of the late ancient Roman world. In addition to filling out the details of Paulinus's life at Nola, Trout looks in depth at Paulinus before his ascetic conversion, providing a new assessment of this formative period to better understand Paulinus's subsequent importance within the influential ascetic and ecclesiastical circles of his age. Trout also highlights Paulinus's place in the swirl of rebellions and heresies of the time, in the pagan revival of the 390s, and especially in the development of a new genre of Christian poetry. And, he examines anew Paulinus's relationships with such figures as Jerome, Rufinus, and Augustine. Trout fully explores the complexity of a figure who has too often been simplified and provides new insights into the kaleidoscopic character of the age in which he lived.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aChristian poetry, LatinxHistory and criticism. 0aChristian saintsxBiographyxItalyxNola. 0aChristian saintsxCorrespondencexItalyxNola. 0aChristian saintszItalyzNolavBiography. 0aChristian saintszItalyzNolavCorrespondence. 0aChristian saintszItalyzNolaxCorrespondence. 0aChristianity and literaturexRome. 0aChristianity and literaturezRome. 0aPoets, LatinxBiographyxItalyxNola. 0aPoets, LatinxCorrespondencexItalyxNola. 0aPoets, LatinzItalyzNolavBiography. 0aPoets, LatinzItalyzNolavCorrespondence. 0aPoets, LatinzItalyzNolaxBiography. 0aPoets, LatinzItalyzNolaxCorrespondence. 4aAncient Archaeology. 4aAncient History. 4aChristianity. 4aNear and Middle Eastern History. 4aOvid. 4aclassical lit